We have recommended to the Municipal Accountant the following courses of action:
Review the transactions charged to Construction in Progress accounts and ensure that only accumulated cost of infrastructure assets, buildings or structures which are still in the process of construction, development or acquisition be recorded thereof;
Make proper reclassification to the appropriate PPE accounts upon completion;
Reconcile with the records of the Office of the Municipal Engineer and disclose the details of Construction in Progress accounts in the notes to financial statements and subsidiary schedule;
Make necessary adjusting or correcting entries and strictly observe the proper accounts prescribed in the Revised Chart of Accounts for Local Government Units for accurate and reliable presentation of the affected accounts in the financial statements.

In view of the foregoing deficiencies, we have recommended the following –
The LGU should exert diligent efforts to locate the necessary documents supporting their claims in order to establish the legitimacy of the receivable accounts;
When a receivable account is confirmed to be non-moving or remained to be inactive in the books of accounts for ten (10) years or more and where settlements or collectability could no longer be ascertained, it shall be considered a dormant receivable account. In this regard, management should be guided by procedures on the write-off of dormant receivable accounts under COA Circular 2016-005 dated December 19, 2016.

In view of the foregoing, we have recommended that Management –
Instruct the Municipal Accountant to transfer the PCSO funds received to the General Fund and ensure that appropriations are provided therefor in the utilization thereof;
Submit copies of Memorandum of Agreement entered into between the LGU with PCSO for CY 2019 indicating the category of programs for which its allocation or funds may be utilized and the reportorial requirements pertaining to its utilization as stated in Section 40 of the 2016 Revised IRR for the Small Town Lottery Operations of the PCSO.

We have recommended that the Municipal Treasurer strictly comply with the provisions of existing laws, rules and regulations in the proper handling, custody and disposition of cash and recording of cash transactions to safeguard the government funds from risk of loss, theft or misuse. For the foregoing deficiencies, we have recommended the following:
The Municipal Treasurer require the collecting officers/field collectors to remit their collections intact or on a daily basis and the Report of Collections and Deposits be prepared at the close of each business day;
The Municipal Treasurer utilize only permanent and bonded revenue collectors to undertake the collection;
The accountable forms be issued in strict numerical sequence; and
Collections should not be utilized for encashment of private checks.

To strengthen the internal control in the use of government vehicles and to regulate fuel consumption of the municipality, we have reiterated our previous year’s audit recommendation that at the end of every month, the agency submit to the COA Audit Team Monthly Reports of Official Travels and Monthly Reports of Official Fuel Consumption for audit purposes as required by COA Circular No. 77-61 dated September 26, 1977. In addition, the following measures are hereby recommended:
Ensure that all Driver’s Trip Tickets are duly approved;
Ensure that all Drivers’ Trip Tickets are dated and properly numbered, and these are recorded in a logbook for control purposes. A separate file for the Driver’s Trip Tickets are to be maintained;
Ensure that purpose and destination are properly indicated;
Ensure that number of kilometers travelled and fuel consumption are also indicated;
Ensure that Driver’s Trip Tickets are properly signed by passengers;
Ensure that dates of travel per Driver’s Trip Ticket are consistent with the dates indicated in the Travel Order and Certificate of Appearance attached on the claims of traveling expenses;
The Head of the Agency, Municipal Accountant and Head of the Requesting Unit have to exercise judgment and discretion in determining the reasonableness of fuel consumption.

We have recommended that Management strictly comply with Section 3.1.2 of COA Circular No. 2009-001 and with the provisions of Republic Act No. 9184. Compliance with foregoing provisions is not only a mere compliance but more so it would facilitate the determination of the legitimacy and validity of the transaction. 

For the foregoing deficiencies noted, we have recommended that –

Annual Procurement Plan (APP) be prepared to ensure that procurements are planned prudently and accurately in consideration of the approved budget;

At least one (1) observer from a duly recognized private group in a sector or discipline relevant to the procurement at hand be invited in all stages of the procurement; 

The recommended time frame for the conduct of Bid Evaluation and Post-Qualification be observed by the Bids and Awards Committee in the procurement of goods and infrastructure projects;

Required documents be submitted to provide a more holistic evaluation/review of all contracts and prevent suspension; and

The Notices of Award and Notices to proceed and the approved contract of projects awarded be posted in the agency website of the procuring entity and any conspicuous place within the premises for wide dissemination.

